body_text.text:
Fish, like all other living organisms, can be infected by virus representatives from most of the virus families. Predominantly described as fish pathogens, these viruses include rhabdoviruses, birnaviruses, herpesviruses, iridoviruses, reoviruses, orthomyxoviruses and retroviruses. In this brief review, the most well characterized viruses from each family will be discussed and tables listing the general characteristics of these fish viral pathogens as well as other less well characterized viruses within the family are included (Table 1, Table 2
). In addition, viral agents that have not been confirmed as the etiologic agent and are tentatively classified are listed separately in Table 3
.
